{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3570911,"name":"","username":"Myles","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/779978/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-28T04:03:55.463Z","cooked":"<p>Hello, so I have presets on my robot for the elevator and for the wrist to do this I have a while loop that sets the speed when its not what it needs to be and breaks out of the loop when it is at the correct height/angle, here is the code:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">while(true){
        double currentPosition2 = -m_intakeArticulatorEncoder.getPosition()/60;
        double currentAngle = currentPosition2*360;
        if (targetAngle &lt; currentAngle -5){
            CoralIntakeArticulatorMotor.set(0.1);
        } else if (targetAngle &gt; currentAngle +5){
            CoralIntakeArticulatorMotor.set(-0.1);
        }
        else{
            CoralIntakeArticulatorMotor.set(0);
            break;
        } }`Preformatted text`
</code></pre>
<p>this works on a basic level but the problem is when it is in the while loop it suspends all other inputs, I could have it so you just hold the button and it does the right heights and stuff because of how I have it loops whatever is happening when you press a button, but that wouldn’t work in the autonomous unless there is a way to run it until it is at the right heigh. But I would prefer to be able to have the preset a press once and done, while it doesn’t prohibit driving, any ideas?/Better ways of doing this?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-03-28T04:08:36.973Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":7,"reads":119,"readers_count":118,"score":58.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":497195,"topic_slug":"presets","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/change-one-letter-of-a-thread-title/466278/87","internal":true,"reflection":true,"title":"Change one letter of a thread title","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":74572,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/presets/497195/1","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3570960,"name":"Tim Winters","username":"ArchdukeTim","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/archduketim/{size}/256125_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-28T04:22:58.259Z","cooked":"<p>There are two ways to improve this:</p>
<h3><a name="p-3570960-dont-use-while-loops-1" class="anchor" href="#p-3570960-dont-use-while-loops-1"></a>Don’t use <code>while</code> loops</h3>
<p>It seems like you’ve already discovered the issues with using them. They lock up the code and prevent anything else from being controlled until they finish. I think it’s great you saw this behavior and correctly attributed it to the while loop.</p>
<p>Without knowing how the rest of the code is set up, it can be hard to tell you exactly what to replace it with. If you’re using the command-based framework, you should make a command that checks the position in the <code>execute</code> function of the command, as this will be called repeatedly.</p>
<h3><a name="p-3570960-dont-use-a-bang-bang-controller-2" class="anchor" href="#p-3570960-dont-use-a-bang-bang-controller-2"></a>Don’t use a bang-bang controller</h3>
<p>The type of control-scheme you’ve implemented is known as ‘bang-bang’. When the current position is below the set point, a static positive output is applied, and when it’s above, a static negative output is applied. This will likely lead to either a) oscillations around your set point since the mechanism will be moving as it passes through the set point, and isn’t told how to slow down, or b) have a large range of error to allow for some area where the mechanism has no output. This is known as tolerance. You have a tolerance of 10 degrees, which is quite a lot for any robotic mechanism.</p>
<p>A better controller would scale the output based on how far the mechanism is from its target, acting like a sort of spring that pulls the mechanism closer, but has more pulling force when it’s farther, and less when it’s closer. WPILib has this sort of controller built in with the <code>PIDController</code> class. You can read more about it <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/introduction/introduction-to-pid.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">here</a></p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-03-28T04:22:58.259Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":69,"readers_count":68,"score":33.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":497195,"topic_slug":"presets","display_username":"Tim Winters","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/introduction/introduction-to-pid.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Introduction to PID — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":2}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":19820,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"78 AIR Strike Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/presets/497195/2","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3570972,"name":"","username":"Myles","avatar_template":"